A more detailed example:
a LSTM (Long Short Term Memory) is a complicated network that could
remember particular obsticals such as a train coming. A standard NEAT
might be both smaller and more efficient if it new nothing about trains.
It would be confident about how to deal with boulders and trenches that
don&#39;t move. The conventional controller would keep track of remembering
where to go.
So in the particular example, the NEAT is doing a good job interacting
with the conventional controller and avoiding the bolders and skillfully
manuevering the ditches the conventional controller knows nothing about,
when all of a sudden, the LSTM becomes very confident that death is a
DARPA locomotive, and now would be a good time to stop. So the LSTM
confidence output goes from low to high very quickly, drowning the
output of the NEAT. The result is most likely to stop the robot right
away. 
This would work on the idea that the LSTM doesn&#39;t know where the robot
is going or how to avoid drowning in a river, the NEAT doesn&#39;t know
anything about trains, and can&#39;t remember where it&#39;s going, and the
conventional controller can use a GPS and ethernet, but doesn&#39;t know
what trains and ditches are.
Any of that make sense?
Chad

